Judge Neil Gorsuch was an excellent choice by the President to join the Supreme Court, and will continue the legacy of originalist thought and devotion to liberty that was the cornerstone of Justice Scalia's time on our nation's highest court.  I am also pleased that Judge Gorsuch has written positively on term limits in the past. In 1992 he wrote,"Recognizing that men are not angels, the Framers of the Constitution put in place a number of institutional checks designed to prevent abuse of the enormous powers they had vested in the legislative branch...A term limit, we suggest, is simply an analogous procedure designed to advance much the same substantive end."

I remain a "no" vote on the American Health Care Act. I cannot support it unless I am convinced it will dramatically lower healthcare costs for folks across America.

I support the President’s decision to pull the AHCA bill today. Throughout this process, I have been consistent in stating that the main goal of any reform bill must be to make healthcare more affordable for hardworking American families. Unfortunately, the AHCA fell short of that goal, and for that reason I could not support it. I believe Congress should slow down and discuss in an open and transparent manner the best solutions to address the real problem: the unsustainably high cost of healthcare in America. I will always do what I think is right for the citizens of Eastern Iowa, not what the political class in Washington wants me to do -- even if that means standing up to my own party.

I voted against the omnibus spending bill today. For the sake of our children & grandchildren we need to get serious about reining in our debt!

Obamacare is collapsing. In Iowa the two largest insurers have already announced their departure from the market, and the third and final insurer is on the verge of leaving as well. This could leave over 70,000 Iowans with zero options for health insurance - it's clear that something needs to be done.   The AHCA will stabilize the market, lower premiums for Iowans, increase choices, reduce taxes, and protect people who have pre-existing conditions. I withheld my support - against the wishes of my own party - until changes were made to ensure that premiums would come down and that we would take care of those who need help by setting aside over $120 billion to assist citizens with pre-existing conditions. After years of higher costs, fewer choices and broken promises under Obamacare, it's time to enact a better system that actually works for Americans.  #IA01

The U.S. Department of State: Consular Affairs has informed our office of a coming "passport surge" and the importance of renewing your passport as early as possible due to longer than normal processing times.  They estimate 48 million passports will expire the next three years, compared to 31 million in the past three.  Please visit travel.state.gov to learn how you can renew your passport, and please feel free to reach out to our district offices at https://blum.house.gov/contact/offices if you need assistance in this or other Federal matters.

Congress must keep working to solve our country's health care problems. The House worked hard to pass a compromise bill that repeals and replaces the broken Obamacare system, and the Senate should do its job and follow suit.   If the Senate can't get it done, we should simply repeal Obamacare with an effective date of two years from now that will encourage both parties to come together to improve our health care system. This week I signed a discharge petition in the House to do just that. This task is too important to give up on and I will keep working hard to find a solution.

My statement on today's Hurricane Relief and Debt Ceiling Vote #IA01  “As the Representative of Iowa’s 1st District, which has seen devastating flooding over the last decade, I absolutely agree on the critical need for additional funding to assist in mitigating and recovering from the effects of natural disasters,” said Congressman Blum. “Though I voted in favor of disaster relief, this funding should have come from a standalone relief package with spending offsets targeting waste, fraud, and abuse in the federal government. I detest the status quo process we witnessed today: a backroom political deal that combined bills of totally different intent.”   Blum also added, “I voted ‘yes’ because those impacted by Hurricanes Harvey and Irma should not suffer because of the repeated failures of career politicians in Washington. For our nation to be in the fiscal position to afford vital funding for FEMA, flood walls, and hurricane recovery, we must take the hard but necessary steps to control our 20 trillion dollar debt that will be passed on to our children and grandchildren.”

My bipartisan bill, H.R. 69, introduced with Rep. Mark Meadows, Ranking Member Elijah Cummings, and Rep. Gerald Connolly was signed into law today! This bill reauthorizes the Office of Special Counsel to ensure whistleblowers are protected to expose waste, fraud, and abuse in federal agencies.

As the Conference Committee decides on details of the final tax reform bill, I've been fighting to ensure the priorities of my district are upheld. First, asking to preserve the medical expense deduction. I've heard from many in my district about the importance of this deduction, described more in the letter below.

My 3rd ask to the Conference Committee: Protect deductions and provisions to support renewable wind energy.   To read the letter and full list of signers, visit: https://blum.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=654
My 2nd ask to the Conference Committee: No expiration date on the reduced individual tax brackets.

My 4th request to the Conference Committee reinforces my consistent efforts to ensure Historic Tax Credits are kept available for the First District.   To read the full letter and list of signers, visit: https://blum.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=643

Despite the millions of dollars spent by special interests to misinform my district, families in Iowa's First District will see their take home pay increase under the House tax reform plan, $2,121 on average.   To everyone who has written and called into my office with specific parts of the bill that they'd like to see improved, thank you for your input. Your thoughtful contributions helped decide the direction for my efforts to the Conference Committee.
Would you like a flag flown over the U.S. Capitol to honor a fellow Iowan in your life? Contact my office or fill out a request at blum.house.gov. We are here to serve!

After taking a look at the Conference report of the new tax bill, I am very happy to see that many of my efforts paid off. Thank you again to everyone who joined in on this process and supported our efforts-- this bill is a big win for #IA01.
